              <h2>How this gas mileage (MPG) calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This tool helps you measure your real-world fuel economy and
                fuel costs. It supports:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>US MPG and UK MPG</li>
                <li>km/L (kilometers per liter)</li>
                <li>L/100 km (liters per 100 kilometers)</li>
                <li>Cost per mile or per kilometer</li>
                <li>Estimated fuel needed and cost for a future trip</li>
              </ul>

              <h3>1. Calculating MPG from a fuel fill-up</h3>
              <p>To measure your actual fuel economy:</p>
              <ol>
                <li>Fill your tank completely and reset your trip odometer.</li>
                <li>Drive as usual until the next fill-up.</li>
                <li>
                  Refill the tank completely and note:
                  <ul>
                    <li>
                      <strong>Distance driven</strong> (miles or km from the
                      trip meter)
                    </li>
                    <li>
                      <strong>Fuel used</strong> (gallons or liters to refill)
                    </li>
                  </ul>
                </li>
                <li>
                  Enter these values in the calculator and click
                  <strong>Calculate</strong>.
                </li>
              </ol>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">Basic MPG formula</p>
                <p>For US MPG:</p>
                <p>
                  \( \text{MPG} = \dfrac{\text{miles driven}}{\text{US gallons
                  used}} \)
                </p>
                <p>For km/L:</p>
                <p>
                  \( \text{km/L} = \dfrac{\text{kilometers driven}}{\text{liters
                  used}} \)
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>2. Converting between MPG, km/L, and L/100 km</h3>
              <p>
                Once we know your fuel economy in one unit, we convert to the
                others using standard factors:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>1 US gallon = 3.78541 liters</li>
                <li>1 UK (imperial) gallon = 4.54609 liters</li>
                <li>1 mile = 1.60934 kilometers</li>
              </ul>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">Key conversion formulas</p>
                <p>From US MPG to L/100 km:</p>
                <p>\( \text{L/100 km} = \dfrac{235.215}{\text{US MPG}} \)</p>
                <p>From L/100 km to km/L:</p>
                <p>\( \text{km/L} = \dfrac{100}{\text{L/100 km}} \)</p>
                <p>From km/L to US MPG:</p>
                <p>
                  \( \text{US MPG} = \text{km/L} \times \dfrac{2.35215}{1} \)
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>3. Fuel cost and trip planning</h3>
              <p>
                If you enter a fuel price per gallon or per liter, the
                calculator also estimates:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li><strong>Cost per mile or per kilometer</strong></li>
                <li><strong>Cost per 100 miles or 100 km</strong></li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Fuel needed and total cost for a planned trip</strong>
                </li>
              </ul>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">Cost formulas</p>
                <p>
                  Let \( P \) be fuel price per unit (gallon or liter), \( F \)
                  be fuel used, and \( D \) be distance:
                </p>
                <p>Total fuel cost: \( C = P \times F \)</p>
                <p>
                  Cost per distance unit: \( \text{Cost per mile/km} =
                  \dfrac{C}{D} \)
                </p>
                <p>For a planned trip distance \( D_{\text{trip}} \):</p>
                <p>
                  Fuel needed: \( F_{\text{trip}} =
                  \dfrac{D_{\text{trip}}}{\text{MPG (or km/L)}} \)
                </p>
                <p>
                  Trip cost: \( C_{\text{trip}} = P \times F_{\text{trip}} \)
                </p>
              </div>

              <h2>What is a good MPG?</h2>
              <p>
                “Good” MPG depends on vehicle type, fuel, and driving
                conditions. As a rough guide:
              </p>
              <ul>
